    {
      "kind": "content",
      "content": [
        {
          "anchor": "discussion",
          "level": 2,
          "text": "Discussion",
          "type": "heading"
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "To implement social features in your app, itâ€™s possible to correlate a user record with the userâ€™s actual name, but your app must get permission from the user to do so. Making a user record discoverable to the contacts of that user involves calling the "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": true,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/cloudkit/ckcontainer/1399174-requestapplicationpermission"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " method and asking for the "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": true,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/cloudkit/ckapplicationpermissions/ckapplicationpermissionuserdiscoverability"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " permission. When you call that method, CloudKit asks the user whether the user record can become discoverable. If the user grants the request, that userâ€™s contacts can discover that userâ€™s true identity when running the app. To discover the contacts of the current user, you use the "
            },
            {
              "type": "codeVoice",
              "code": "discoverAllContactUserInfosWithCompletionHandler:"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " method or one of several other methods to get the related user information."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "The first time you request a permission on any of the userâ€™s devices, the user receives a prompt to grant or deny the request. After the user grants or denies a permission, subsequent requests for the same permission (on the same or separate devices), donâ€™t prompt the user again."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "This method runs asynchronously, and the system calls your completion handler on an arbitary queue and provides the outcome."
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    }
